\par
\b B. DISCLAIMER\par
\b0 These routines are intended to illustrate examples in the text  and  to\par
provide starting points for users' own programs.  While  they  have  been\par
thoroughly tested, there may be small errors or bugs.  The   authors  and\par
the publisher take no responsibility and  offer  no  warranties  on  this\par
software. The user must assume all risk and  responsibility  when  using\par
these routines.\par
\par
\b C. Organization of the C++ Routines\par
\b0 The files are in the directory \\cpp and are organized into subdirectories  \par
\\Chapt-5, \\Chapt-6, etc. An additional subdirectory, \\CppLibrary, includes \par
files with routines that may be used by more than one program. A list of all \par
files follows these comments.\par
\par
In general, the subdirectories for each chapter include:\par
1. Main program with local functions;\par
2. References through their prototypes to files of library routines;\par
3. One or more local file of routines specific to the programs in the chapter, \par
   referenced through their prototypes.   \par
4. Data and parameter files with extensions .dat and .par respectively.\par
\par
Chapters 6 through 9 contain discussions and example of methods for fitting \par
functions to data samples.  The sample programs for each of these chapters include\par
a local file of fitting utilities (e.e., FitUtil-ch6.cpp) and reference to a library \par
file of utility programs, \\CppLibrary\\GenUtil.cpp).  (A single file, FitUtil.cpp,\par
which includes all fitting methods discussed in these chapters, is available \par
in \\CppLibrary. Most of the calling programs in Chapters 7 through 9 \par
should work with this comprehensive file.)  Sample data files are also included.\par
\par
\b D. Suggested Procedure\par
\b0 If possible, copy the C++ files and subdirectories to a hard drive, preserving \par
the directory structure, i.e., the base directory should be c:\\cpp. This will \par
avoid the necessity of changing the references to "include" files and data files. \par
\par
\cf2\f2\fs22 However, compressing and decompressing the programs changes the names of the subdirectories.  \cf1 Therefore, \par
before running the programs you must rename all  11 subdirectories so that they are consistent with the file name \par
references in the programs. For example, names of the form "Chapt05" must be changed to the form "Chapt-5", "Chapt10" becomes "Chapt-10", and "Append_A" becomes "Append-A."\cf2\par
\cf1\f1\fs20\par
\cf0 Feel free to experiment with the routines  and to make  changes  to  suit\par
particular applications.\par
\par
